10    /**
11    * Bean properties are logical entities that represent data
12    * that Java objects (POJOs (Plain Old Java Objects), sometimes also called "beans")
13    * contain; and that are accessed using accessors (methods like getters
14    * and setters, fields, contstructor parametrers).
15    * Instances allow access to annotations directly associated
16    * to property (via field or method), as well as contextual
17    * annotations (annotations for class that contains properties).
18    *<p>
19    * Instances are not typically passed when constructing serializers
20    * and deserializers, but rather only passed when context
21    * is known when
22    * {@link com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ser.ContextualSerializer} and
23    * {@link com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.deser.ContextualDeserializer}
24    * resolution occurs (<code>createContextual(...)</code> method is called).
25    * References may (need to) be retained by serializers and deserializers,
26    * especially when further resolving dependant handlers like value
27    * serializers/deserializers or structured types.
28    */
